## What happened

`DSA` has been on the deprecation path since **.NET 7** (warning **SYSLIB0030**). On macOS, Apple's native crypto frameworks (`Security.framework` / `CryptoKit`) dropped DSA years ago, so .NET was relying on an **OpenSSL compatibility shim** to keep `DSA.Create()` working.

In .NET 11, Microsoft completed the deprecation: `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS because the platform shim for the obsoleted algorithm is no longer shipped.

Linux and Windows still have native OS-level DSA support, which is why those builds continue to work.

## How to fix it

**Best option — migrate away from DSA entirely.** DSA is a legacy algorithm with limited key sizes. Use **ECDSA** or **Ed25519** (`ECDsa.Create()`) for new signatures.

**If you must verify existing legacy DSA signatures**, use **BouncyCastle**, which implements DSA in pure managed code with no platform dependency:

```bash
dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
```

```csharp
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Signers;
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

public static bool VerifyLegacyDsa(byte[] publicKeyDer, byte[] message, byte[] signature)
{
    var keyParam = (DsaPublicKeyParameters)PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyDer);
    var signer = new DsaSigner();
    signer.Init(forSigning: false, keyParam);

    // DSA signatures are (r, s) — decode from DER or raw as needed
    var (r, s) = DecodeDerSignature(signature);
    return signer.VerifySignature(SHA1.HashData(message), r, s);
}
```

This runs identically on Linux, Windows, and macOS with no native crypto dependency.
